Concepts.definition: A bruise due to trauma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The creation of hematoma outside the arterial wall following bleeding due to puncture of the arterial wall. Pseudoaneurysms can also occur in the heart chambers following myocardial infarction and bleeding.

Concepts.definition: The creation of hematoma outside the arterial wall following bleeding due to puncture of the arterial wall. Pseudoaneurysms can also occur in the heart chambers following myocardial infarction and bleeding.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sustained and usually painful contraction of muscle fibers. This may occur as an isolated phenomenon or as a manifestation of an underlying disease process (e.g., UREMIA; HYPOTHYROIDISM; MOTOR NEURON DISEASE; etc.). (From Adams et al., Principles of Neurology, 6th ed, p1398)

Concepts.definition: A sustained, sudden and involuntary contraction of a muscle or group of muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A progressive condition usually characterized by combined failure of the lungs, liver, kidney, and clotting mechanisms.

Concepts.definition: Complete impairment of two or more organs or organ systems.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A congenital anatomic abnormality manifested during the neonatal period.

Concepts.definition: A congenital anatomic abnormality manifested during the neonatal period.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Shock resulting from neurogenic vasodilation, which can be produced by cerebral trauma or hemorrhage, spinal cord injury, deep general or spinal anesthesia, or toxic central nervous system depression.

Concepts.definition: Shock resulting from neurogenic vasodilation, which can be produced by cerebral trauma or hemorrhage, spinal cord injury, deep general or spinal anesthesia, or toxic central nervous system depression.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Obstruction or a closure of hollow organ, passageway or vessel; also the transient approximation of the edges of a natural opening; imperforation.

Concepts.definition: Obstruction or a closure of hollow organ, passageway or vessel; also the transient approximation of the edges of a natural opening; imperforation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A transitory alteration in movement, sensation or autonomic nerve function due to abnormal electric activity in a localized area of the cerebral cortex, usually without change in awareness or alertness. Symptoms vary with different lesion locations and may include but not limited to the motor (e.g. rhythmic muscle contractions in one area of the body), somatosensory and sensory alterations manifested by abnormal numbness, paresthesias or other hallucinations, including several types of aura; autonomic and psychic symptoms, e.g. with changes in speech, thought, personality, mood, sensation of deja vu or hallucinations.

Concepts.definition: A transitory alteration in movement, sensation or autonomic nerve function due to abnormal electric activity in a localized area of the cerebral cortex, usually without change in awareness or alertness. Symptoms vary with different lesion locations and may include but not limited to the motor (e.g. rhythmic muscle contractions in one area of the body), somatosensory and sensory alterations manifested by abnormal numbness, paresthesias or other hallucinations, including several types of aura; autonomic and psychic symptoms, e.g. with changes in speech, thought, personality, mood, sensation of deja vu or hallucinations.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Changed definition to match current NCIt per NHLBI request. 9.7.18 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A simple partial seizure consisting of clonus or spasm of a muscle or muscle group; it may be single or in a continuous and repetitive series or may spread to adjacent muscles.

Concepts.definition: A simple partial seizure consisting of clonus or spasm of a muscle or muscle group; it may be single or in a continuous and repetitive series or may spread to adjacent muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Paralysis of the nerves located in the legs.

Concepts.definition: Paralysis of the nerves located in the legs.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Injury occurring as a result of the delivery process.

Concepts.definition: Injury to the brain of a newborn infant occurring around the time of birth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A nonimmunologic, chemically induced type of photosensitivity.

Concepts.definition: A nonimmunologic, chemically induced type of photosensitivity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Diseases characterized by inflammation involving multiple muscles. This may occur as an acute or chronic condition associated with medication toxicity (DRUG TOXICITY, NERVOUS SYSTEM); CONNECTIVE TISSUE DISEASES; infections; malignant NEOPLASMS; and other disorders. The term polymyositis is frequently used to refer to a specific clinical entity characterized by subacute or slowly progressing symmetrical weakness primarily affecting the proximal limb and trunk muscles. The illness may occur at any age, but is most frequent in the fourth to sixth decade of life. Weakness of pharyngeal and laryngeal muscles, interstitial lung disease, and inflammation of the myocardium may also occur. Muscle biopsy reveals widespread destruction of segments of muscle fibers and an inflammatory cellular response. (Adams et al., Principles of Neurology, 6th ed, pp1404-9)

Concepts.definition: An idiopathic inflammatory disorder affecting the muscles. It presents with symmetrical proximal muscle weakness and elevated skeletal muscle enzymes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The backflow of blood from the pulmonary artery into the right ventricle, owing to insufficiency of the pulmonic semilunar valve.

Concepts.definition: The backflow of blood from the pulmonary artery into the right ventricle, owing to insufficiency of the pulmonic semilunar valve.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Drooping of the upper eyelid.

Concepts.definition: The drooping of the upper eyelid.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Radiation induced skin desquamation

Concepts.definition: The complex of symptoms characterizing the disease known as radiation injury, resulting from excessive exposure (greater than 200 rads or 2 gray) of the whole body (or large part) to ionizing radiation. The earliest of these symptoms are nausea, fatigue, vomiting, and diarrhea, which may be followed by epilation, hemorrhage, inflammation of the mouth and throat, and general loss of energy. In severe cases, where the radiation exposure has been approximately 1000 Rad (10 gray) or more, death may occur within two to four weeks. Those who survive six weeks after the receipt of a single large dose of radiation to the whole body may generally be expected to recover. (U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Shock resulting from primary failure of the heart in its pumping function, as in myocardial infarction, severe cardiomyopathy, or mechanical obstruction or compression of the heart.

Concepts.definition: Shock resulting from primary failure of the heart in its pumping function, as in myocardial infarction, severe cardiomyopathy, or mechanical obstruction or compression of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A cutaneous inflammatory reaction occurring as a result of exposure to biologically effective levels of ionizing radiation.

Concepts.definition: A cutaneous inflammatory reaction occurring as a result of exposure to biologically effective levels of ionizing radiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bluish or purplish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes resulting from a reduced amount of oxygenated hemoglobin in the blood.

Concepts.definition: A bluish or purplish discoloration of the skin and mucous membranes resulting from a reduced concentration of oxygenated hemoglobin in the blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Regular uterine activity with associated cervical change prior to 37 weeks gestation.

Concepts.definition: Regular uterine activity with associated cervical change prior to 37 weeks gestation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A symptom consisting of the involuntary expulsion of air from the nose.

Concepts.definition: A symptom consisting of the involuntary expulsion of air from the nose.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Narrowing or stricture of a vessel, duct or canal.

Concepts.definition: Narrowing or stricture of a vessel, duct or canal.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Inflammation of the lungs.

Concepts.definition: An acute, acute and chronic, or chronic inflammation focally or diffusely affecting the lung parenchyma, due to infections (viruses, fungi, mycoplasma, or bacteria), treatment (e.g. radiation), or exposure (inhalation) to chemicals. Symptoms include cough, shortness of breath, fevers, chills, chest pain, headache, sweating, and weakness.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder resulting from loss of function or tissue destruction of an organ or multiple organs, arising from humoral or cellular immune responses of the individual to his own tissue constituents. It may be systemic (e.g., systemic lupus erythematosus), or organ specific, (e.g., thyroiditis).

Concepts.definition: A disorder resulting from loss of function or tissue destruction of an organ or multiple organs, arising from humoral or cellular immune responses of the individual to his own tissue constituents. It may be systemic (e.g., systemic lupus erythematosus), or organ specific, (e.g., thyroiditis).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A heterogeneous group of disorders, some hereditary, others acquired, characterized by abnormal structure or function of one or more of the elements of connective tissue, i.e., collagen, elastin, or the mucopolysaccharides.

Concepts.definition: A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the connective tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A decrease in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.

Concepts.definition: A decrease in the fraction of the forced vital capacity that is exhaled in a specific number of seconds.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any physical or mental impairment that interferes with an individual's ability to perform desired activities.

Concepts.definition: Any physical or mental impairment that interferes with an individual's ability to perform desired activities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Difficult, painful breathing or shortness of breath.

Concepts.definition: An uncomfortable sensation of difficulty breathing. It may present as an acute or chronic sign of an underlying respiratory or heart disorder.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A state due to excess retention of carbon dioxide in the body.

Concepts.definition: A condition in which the blood pH is less than normal, secondary to impaired gas exchange.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Enlargement or overgrowth of the myocardium of the right ventricle, due chronic pressure overload.

Concepts.definition: Enlargement or overgrowth of the myocardium of the right ventricle, due chronic pressure overload.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Failure of proper functioning of the right ventricle, with venous engorgement, hepatic enlargement, and subcutaneous edema.

Concepts.definition: Failure of proper functioning of the right ventricle, with venous engorgement, hepatic enlargement, and subcutaneous edema.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A traumatic or pathologic injury to the bones of the skull in which the continuity of the bones of the skull is broken.

Concepts.definition: A traumatic or pathologic injury to the bones of the skull in which the continuity of the bones of the skull is broken.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Traumatic damage of the spinal cord.

Concepts.definition: Traumatic damage of the spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Bleeding in the area between the scalp and the skull.

Concepts.definition: Bleeding between the scalp and the periosteum.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An unexpected natural death from a cardiac cause within a short time period, generally less than 1 hour from the onset of symptoms, in a person without any prior condition that would appear fatal. SCD is most likely to occur in a patient with an underlying cardiac abnormality, whether known or not; approximately 70% of SCDs are caused by coronary heart disease. A loss of heart function is often attributed to a cardiac arrhythmia, but classifications based on clinical circumstances cannot be considered definitive.

Concepts.definition: An unexpected natural death from a cardiac cause within a short time period from the onset of symptoms.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Infection associated with no detectable symptoms but caused by microorganisms capable of producing easily recognizable diseases, such a poliomyelitis or mumps.

Concepts.definition: Infection associated with no detectable symptoms but caused by microorganisms capable of producing easily recognizable diseases, such a poliomyelitis or mumps.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Inflammation of a synovial membrane.

Concepts.definition: Inflammation of a synovial membrane.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Broken tooth affecting any portion of tooth: root fracture, crown-root, broken tooth (crown fracture), chipped tooth. A crown fracture can involve the pulp. Tooth fracture sequelae range in severity from cosmetic defects to tooth death. Involvement of the pulp is a more important indicator of severity of tooth fracture than is the amount of the tooth affected.

Concepts.definition: Broken tooth affecting any portion of tooth: root fracture, crown-root, broken tooth (crown fracture), chipped tooth. A crown fracture can involve the pulp. Tooth fracture sequelae range in severity from cosmetic defects to tooth death. Involvement of the pulp is a more important indicator of severity of tooth fracture than is the amount of the tooth affected.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Incomplete closure of the tricuspid valve, resulting in tricuspid regurgitation; it is usually secondary to systolic overload in the right ventricle.

Concepts.definition: Dysfunction of the pulmonary valve characterized by incomplete valve closure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Unintended reaction in nervous system caused by electrical stimulation.

Concepts.definition: Unintended reaction in nervous system caused by electrical stimulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: For complications that occur secondary to intraocular lens implantation in the anterior chamber; caused by rubbing of the lens loop (haptics).

Concepts.definition: Clinical triad of uveitis, glaucoma, and hyphema (UGH), especially associated with the early anterior chamber intraocular lens (IOL). Glaucoma is believed to be caused by movement of the IOL against the iris causing release of inflammatory and red blood cell debris, which obstruct the trabecular meshwork. The haptic also may cause direct damage to the trabecular meshwork contributing to the glaucoma. Incidence of UGH is dependent on both surgical methodology applied in the cataract population and type of IOL used. UGH is particularly common if metal clip lenses have been used. Components of the condition may be reversed if the offending IOL is removed before permanent damage has occurred.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Vertigo is a feeling of movement, a sensation as if the external world were revolving around the patient (objective vertigo) or as if he himself were revolving in space (subjective vertigo).  Vertigo is medically distinct from dizziness, lightheadedness, and unsteadiness.

Concepts.definition: A feeling of movement, a sensation as if the external world were revolving around the patient (objective vertigo) or as if he himself were revolving in space (subjective vertigo). Vertigo is medically distinct from dizziness, lightheadedness, and unsteadiness.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachyarrhythmia characterized by smooth undulating waves with QRS complexes merged with T waves at a rate of approximately 250 per minute.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of a high ventricular rate (180 to 250 beats per minute) with a regular rhythm and large oscillating sine wave-like complexes occurring as a result of QRS complexes and T waves being merged. The P wave is not visible.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormal changes in skin coloration.

Concepts.definition: Abnormal skin coloration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Painful sensation in the abdominal region.

Concepts.definition: Painful sensation in the abdominal region.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Accumulation of purulent material in tissues, organs, or circumscribed spaces, usually associated with signs of infection.

Concepts.definition: An inflammatory process characterized by the accumulation of pus within a newly formed tissue cavity which is the result of a bacterial, fungal, or parasitic infection or the presence of a foreign body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pertaining to or characterized by cognition. That operation of the mind which we become aware of objects of thought or perception; it includes all aspects of perceiving, thinking, or remembering.

Concepts.definition: Pertaining to or characterized by cognition. That operation of the mind which we become aware of objects of thought or perception; it includes all aspects of perceiving, thinking, or remembering.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by systematic and extensive loss of memory.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by systematic and extensive loss of memory.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Narrowing of the orifice of the aortic valve or of the supravalvular or subvalvular regions.

Concepts.definition: Narrowing of the orifice of the aortic valve.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Arrhythmia; an abnormal rate of muscle contractions in the heart.

Concepts.definition: Any variation from the normal rate or rhythm (which may include the origin of the impulse and/or its subsequent propagation) in the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A chronic respiratory disease manifested as difficulty breathing due to the narrowing of bronchial passageways.

Concepts.definition: A chronic respiratory disease manifested as difficulty breathing due to the narrowing of bronchial passageways.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An alteration in body temperature outside the normal range.

Concepts.definition: An alteration in body temperature outside the normal range.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by a sudden contraction of the smooth muscles of the bronchial wall.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by a sudden contraction of the smooth muscles of the bronchial wall.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Injury of the soft tissues or bone without breaking the skin, as by a blow. (from Dictionary.com)

Concepts.definition: Injury of the soft tissues or bone without breaking the skin that is characterized by blood leakage into the surrounding area.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An acute, spreading infection of the deep tissues of the skin and muscle that causes the skin to become warm and tender and may also cause fever, chills, swollen lymph nodes, and blisters.

Concepts.definition: Inflammation of the dermis and subcutaneous tissues caused by a bacterial infection. Symptoms include erythema, edema, and pain to the affected area.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pain in the chest.

Concepts.definition: Pain in the chest.

PermissibleValues.value: Contamination From Blood Or Body Fluids
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Contamination From Blood Or Body Fluids

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Contamination From Blood Or Body Fluids
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The patient becomes contaminated from contact with blood/fluids on a device.

Concepts.definition: The patient becomes contaminated from contact with blood/fluids on a device.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormally low body temperature.

Concepts.definition: Abnormally low body temperature.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Loss of intellectual abilities interfering with an individual's social and occupational functions. Causes include Alzheimer's disease, brain injuries, brain tumors, and vascular disorders.

Concepts.definition: Loss of intellectual abilities interfering with an individual's social and occupational functions. Causes include Alzheimer's disease, brain injuries, brain tumors, and vascular disorders.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A severe, often fatal encephalopathy which has been attributed to accumulation in the brain of aluminum from dialysate prepared with inadequately purified water.

Concepts.definition: A severe, often fatal encephalopathy which has been attributed to accumulation in the brain of aluminum from dialysate prepared with inadequately purified water.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Dizziness is a medically indistinct term used to describe a variety of conditions such as lightheadedness, unsteadiness, giddiness, a sense of turning, spinning or rocking.

Concepts.definition: A sensation of lightheadedness, unsteadiness, turning, spinning or rocking.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Accumulation of an excessive amount of fluid in cells or intercellular tissues.

Concepts.definition: Accumulation of an excessive amount of fluid in cells or intercellular tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Changes in cardiac electrical activity.

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a change in cardiac electrical activity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the internal structures of the eye.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by an infectious process involving the internal structures of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The formation of fibrous tissue.

Concepts.definition: The formation of fibrous tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A kingdom of eukaryotic, heterotrophic organisms that live as saprobes or parasites, including mushrooms, yeasts, smuts, molds, etc. They reproduce either sexually or asexually, and have life cycles that range from simple to complex. Filamentous fungi refer to those that grow as multicellular colonies (mushrooms and molds).

Concepts.definition: A kingdom of eukaryotic, heterotrophic organisms that live as saprobes or parasites, including mushrooms, yeasts, smuts, molds, etc. They reproduce either sexually or asexually, and have life cycles that range from simple to complex. Filamentous fungi refer to those that grow as multicellular colonies (mushrooms and molds).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Disruption of the integrity of the erythrocyte membrane causing release of hemoglobin.

Concepts.definition: Disruption of the integrity of the erythrocyte membrane causing release of hemoglobin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A traumatic injury to the head.

Concepts.definition: A traumatic injury to the head.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Increased pressure in the eyeball due to obstruction of the outflow of aqueous humor.

Concepts.definition: Increased pressure in the eyeball due to obstruction of the outflow of aqueous humor.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Bleeding or escape of blood from a vessel.

Concepts.definition: The flow of blood from a ruptured blood vessel.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormally high level of glucose in the blood.

Concepts.definition: Abnormally high level of glucose in the blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by the persistent or recurrent inability to achieve or to maintain an erection during sexual activity.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by the persistent or recurrent inability to achieve or to maintain an erection during sexual activity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Damage inflicted on the body as the direct or indirect result of an external force, with or without disruption of structural continuity.

Concepts.definition: Damage inflicted on the body as the direct or indirect result of an external force, with or without disruption of structural continuity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Bleeding within the cranium.

Concepts.definition: Bleeding within the cranium.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormal perception of sounds experienced by an individual in the absence of auditory stimulation.

Concepts.definition: Abnormal perception of sounds experienced by an individual in the absence of auditory stimulation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A transient, itchy skin eruption characterized by wheals with pale interiors and red margins.

Concepts.definition: A transient, itchy skin eruption characterized by wheals with pale interiors and red margins.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An infectious agent which consists of two parts, genetic material and a protein coat. These organisms lack independent metabolism, and they must infect the cells of other types of organisms to reproduce. Most viruses are capable of passing through fine filters that retain bacteria, and are not visible through a light microscope.

Concepts.definition: An infectious agent which consists of two parts, genetic material and a protein coat. These organisms lack independent metabolism, and they must infect the cells of other types of organisms to reproduce. Most viruses are capable of passing through fine filters that retain bacteria, and are not visible through a light microscope.

ValueMeaning.changeDescription: Updated definition to match current NCIt. 11.24.2020 mc

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A change from the patient's baseline sleeping pattern, either an increase or a decrease in the number of hours slept. This can also refer to alterations in the stages of sleep.

Concepts.definition: A change from the patient's baseline sleeping pattern, in the hours slept and/or an alteration/dysfunction in the stages of sleep.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Anemia resulting from the premature destruction of the peripheral blood red cells. It may be congenital or it may be caused by infections, medications, or malignancies.

Concepts.definition: Anemia resulting from the premature destruction of the peripheral blood red cells. It may be congenital or it may be caused by infections, medications, or malignancies.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Urination at short intervals; it may result from increased urine formation, decreased bladder capacity, or lower urinary tract irritation.

Concepts.definition: Urination at short intervals; it may result from increased urine formation, decreased bladder capacity, or lower urinary tract irritation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pain in a joint.

Concepts.definition: Pain in a joint.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Complete failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction through the AV node to the ventricles.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of complete failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles. This is manifested on the ECG by disassociation of atrial and ventricular rhythms. The atrial rate must be faster than the ventricular rate. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Human immunodeficiency virus. Species of LENTIVIRUS, subgenus primate lentiviruses (LENTIVIRUSES, PRIMATE), formerly designated T-cell lymphotropic virus type III/lymphadenopathy-associated virus (HTLV-III/LAV). It is acknowledged to be the agent responsible for the acute infectious manifestations, neurologic disorders, and immunologic abnormalities linked to the ACQUIRED IMMUNODEFICIENCY SYNDROME.

Concepts.definition: The virus isolated and recognized as the etiologic agent of AIDS. HIV-1 is classified as a lentivirus, a subtype of retroviruses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A subperiosteal hemorrhage limited to the surface of one cranial bone, a usually benign condition seen in the newborn as a result of bone trauma.

Concepts.definition: A subperiosteal hemorrhage limited to the surface of one cranial bone, a usually benign condition seen in the newborn as a result of bone trauma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Acute compression of the heart caused by increased intrapericardial pressure due to the collection of blood or fluid in the pericardium from rupture of the heart, penetrating trauma, or progressive effusion.

Concepts.definition: Acute compression of the heart caused by increased intrapericardial pressure due to the collection of blood or fluid in the pericardium from rupture of the heart, penetrating trauma, or progressive effusion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Watery bowel movements.

Concepts.definition: Watery bowel movements.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An abnormal pregnancy in which the conception is implanted outside the endometrial cavity.

Concepts.definition: An abnormal pregnancy in which the conception is implanted outside the endometrial cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A functional and/or structural disorder of the brain caused by diseases (e.g. liver disease, kidney disease), medications, chemicals, and injuries.

Concepts.definition: A functional and/or structural disorder of the brain caused by diseases (e.g. liver disease, kidney disease), medications, chemicals, and injuries.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Caused by conditions such as inadequate placental function (often abruptio placentae), preeclamptic toxicity, prolapse of the umbilical cord, or complications from anesthetic administration.

Concepts.definition: Hypoxia in utero, caused by conditions such as inadequate placental function (often abruptio placentae), preeclamptic toxicity, prolapse of the umbilical cord, or complications from anesthetic administration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A condition characterized by an abnormally high body temperature. In a hyperthermic state, the hypothalamic set-point is normal but body temperature increases and overrides the ability to lose heat, resulting from exogenous heat exposure or endogenous heat production.

Concepts.definition: A condition characterized by an abnormally high body temperature. In a hyperthermic state, the hypothalamic set-point is normal but body temperature increases and overrides the ability to lose heat, resulting from exogenous heat exposure or endogenous heat production.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The obstruction of the pulmonary artery or one of its branches by an embolus, sometimes associated with infarction of the lung.

Concepts.definition: The obstruction of the pulmonary artery or one of its branches by an embolus, sometimes associated with infarction of the lung.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A spontaneous loss of consciousness caused by insufficient blood supply to the brain.

Concepts.definition: A spontaneous loss of consciousness caused by insufficient blood supply to the brain.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any disease caused by a virus.

Concepts.definition: Any disease caused by a virus.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Increased amounts of fluid within the pleural cavity. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough, and chest pain. It is usually caused by lung infections, congestive heart failure, pleural and lung tumors, connective tissue disorders, and trauma.

Concepts.definition: Increased amounts of fluid within the pleural cavity. Symptoms include shortness of breath, cough, and chest pain. It is usually caused by lung infections, congestive heart failure, pleural and lung tumors, connective tissue disorders, and trauma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Death of tissue due to external pressure.

Concepts.definition: Death of tissue due to external pressure.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Acute or chronic condition, characterized by the inability of the kidneys to adequately filter the blood substances, resulting in uremia and electrolyte imbalances. Acute renal failure is usually associated with oliguria or anuria, hyperkalemia, and pulmonary edema. Chronic renal failure is irreversible and requires hemodialysis.

Concepts.definition: An acute or chronic condition that is characterized by the inability of the kidneys to adequately filter the blood.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Long-standing and persistent renal disease with glomerular filtration rate (GFR) less than 15 ml/min.

Concepts.definition: Long-standing and persistent renal disease with glomerular filtration rate (GFR) less than 15 ml/min.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Overall tiredness and lack of energy.

Concepts.definition: Overall tiredness and lack of energy.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A collection of blood in the pleural cavity.

Concepts.definition: A collection of blood in the pleural cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The sensation of discomfort, distress, or agony, resulting from the stimulation of specialized nerve endings.

Concepts.definition: The sensation of discomfort, distress, or agony, resulting from the stimulation of specialized nerve endings.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormal presence of air in the pleural cavity.

Concepts.definition: Abnormal presence of air in the pleural cavity.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The formation of new tissue in the process of wound healing.

Concepts.definition: A permanent mark left on the skin in the process of wound healing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The presence of pathogenic microorganisms in the blood stream causing a rapidly progressing systemic reaction that may lead to shock. Symptoms include fever, chills, tachycardia, and increased respiratory rate. It is a medical emergency that requires urgent medical attention.

Concepts.definition: The presence of pathogenic microorganisms in the blood stream causing a rapidly progressing systemic reaction that may lead to shock. Symptoms include fever, chills, tachycardia, and increased respiratory rate. It is a medical emergency that requires urgent medical attention.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Partial or complete loss of the ability to detect or understand sounds resulting from damage to the outer, middle, or inner ear structures. Causes include exposure to loud noise, ear infections, injuries to the ear, genetic, and congenital disorders.

Concepts.definition: Partial or complete loss of the ability to detect or understand sounds resulting from damage to the outer, middle, or inner ear structures. Causes include exposure to loud noise, ear infections, injuries to the ear, genetic, and congenital disorders.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Shock resulting from insufficient blood volume for the maintenance of adequate cardiac output, blood pressure and tissue perfusion.

Concepts.definition: Shock resulting from insufficient blood volume for the maintenance of adequate cardiac output, blood pressure and tissue perfusion.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An abnormal increase in the number of cells in an organ or a tissue with consequent enlargement.

Concepts.definition: An abnormal increase in the number of cells in an organ or a tissue with consequent enlargement.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Inflammatory intraocular reaction with clouding and cells in vitreous; often accompanies inflammation of ciliary body, iris, choroid, or retina.

Concepts.definition: Inflammatory intraocular reaction with clouding and cells in vitreous; often accompanies inflammation of ciliary body, iris, choroid, or retina.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intense reaction (usually immunologic) developing at the site of injection

Concepts.definition: An intense reaction (usually immunologic) developing at the site of injection

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abortion brought on intentionally.

Concepts.definition: Abortion brought on intentionally.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A condition in which the skin and the whites of the eyes become yellow, urine darkens, and the color of stool becomes lighter than normal. Jaundice occurs when the liver is not working properly or when a bile duct is blocked.

Concepts.definition: Yellow pigmentation of the skin, mucous membranes, and the eyes due to hyperbilirubinemia. Causes include liver disease, biliary tract obstruction, and hemolysis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by inflammation to the cornea of the eye.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by inflammation to the cornea of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Headache in erect position, after lumbar puncture; due to lowering of intracranial pressure by leakage of cerebrospinal fluid through the needle tract.

Concepts.definition: Headache in erect position, after lumbar puncture; due to lowering of intracranial pressure by leakage of cerebrospinal fluid through the needle tract.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Narrowing of the left atrioventricular mitral orifice.

Concepts.definition: Narrowing of the left atrioventricular mitral orifice.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bruise to the heart.

Concepts.definition: A bruise to the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sudden, violent, involuntary contraction of a muscle or group of muscles.

Concepts.definition: A sudden, violent, involuntary contraction of a muscle or group of muscles.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by inflammation of the muscle tissue of the heart.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by inflammation of the muscle tissue of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The formation of new or recent blood vessels. The vasculature network is critical to the development of neoplasms. As the tumor burden grows, vascular endothial cells are recruited to form new blood vessels as an increased demand for blood and nourishment is required.

Concepts.definition: The formation of new or recent blood vessels. The vasculature network is critical to the development of neoplasms. As the tumor burden grows, vascular endothelial cells are recruited to form new blood vessels as an increased demand for blood and nourishment is required.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A cell death process that is morphologically characterized by a gain in cell volume (oncosis), swelling of organelles, plasma membrane rupture and subsequent loss of intracellular contents.

Concepts.definition: A cell death process that is morphologically characterized by a gain in cell volume (oncosis), swelling of organelles, plasma membrane rupture and subsequent loss of intracellular contents.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Damage to the eye.

Concepts.definition: Damage to the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Decreased calcification or density of bone tissue.

Concepts.definition: Decreased calcification or density of bone tissue.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A general term most often used to describe severe or complete loss of muscle strength due to motor system disease from the level of the cerebral cortex to the muscle fiber. This term may also occasionally refer to a loss of sensory function. (From Adams et al., Principles of Neurology, 6th ed, p45)

Concepts.definition: Partial or complete loss of function of one or more muscles. It is usually caused by damage to the nervous system.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any disorder affecting blood flow through the veins or arteries outside of the heart.

Concepts.definition: Any disorder affecting blood flow through the veins or arteries outside of the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Inflammation of the throat most often caused by viral and bacterial infections. Other causes include allergens, chemical substances, and trauma.

Concepts.definition: Inflammation of the throat most often caused by viral and bacterial infections. Other causes include allergens, chemical substances, and trauma.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A usually small tearing of the retina occurring when the vitreous separates from the retina.  It may lead to retinal detachment.  Symptoms include flashes and floaters.

Concepts.definition: A usually small tearing of the retina occurring when the vitreous separates from the retina. It may lead to retinal detachment. Symptoms include flashes and floaters.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Impairment of the right ventricular function associated with low ejection fraction and decreased motility of the right ventricular wall.

Concepts.definition: Impairment of the right ventricular function associated with low ejection fraction and decreased motility of the right ventricular wall.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A finding of tumor-like collection of serum in the tissues.

Concepts.definition: A finding of tumor-like collection of serum in the tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any kind of inflammatory process of the tonsils, pharynx, or/and larynx characterized by pain in swallowing.

Concepts.definition: Any kind of inflammatory process of the tonsils, pharynx, or/and larynx characterized by pain in swallowing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Cerebral hemorrhage into the subdural space. See also Stroke Syndrome.

Concepts.definition: Bleeding between the dura mater and the brain, usually secondary to a tear of the bridging vein.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Intracranial hemorrhage into the subarachnoid space.

Concepts.definition: Intracranial hemorrhage into the subarachnoid space.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Tachycardia; an abnormally rapid heartbeat, usually applied to a heart rate above 100 per minute.

Concepts.definition: An abnormally rapid heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Rapid breathing.

Concepts.definition: Abnormal increase of rate of breathing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The condition resulting from the spread of bacterial products (toxins) by the bloodstream.

Concepts.definition: The condition resulting from the spread of bacterial products (toxins) by the bloodstream.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by inflammation to the uvea of the eye.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by inflammation to the uvea of the eye.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An infectious process affecting the upper respiratory tract (nose, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, larynx, or trachea). Symptoms include congestion, sneezing, coughing, fever, and sore throat.

Concepts.definition: An infectious process affecting the upper respiratory tract (nose, paranasal sinuses, pharynx, larynx, or trachea). Symptoms include congestion, sneezing, coughing, fever, and sore throat.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sudden compelling urge to urinate.

Concepts.definition: An acute and compelling urge to urinate.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Sudden drop of the blood pressure, bradycardia, and peripheral vasodilation that may lead to loss of consciousness. It results from an increase in the activity of the vagus nerve. It may be triggered by emotions of fear or pain or gastrointestinal upset and may be relieved by lying down while keeping the legs elevated.

Concepts.definition: Sudden drop of the blood pressure, bradycardia, and peripheral vasodilation that may lead to loss of consciousness. It results from an increase in the activity of the vagus nerve. It may be triggered by emotions of fear or pain or gastrointestinal upset and may be relieved by lying down while keeping the legs elevated.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Damage to a blood vessel resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.

Concepts.definition: Damage to a blood vessel resulting from a full thickness disruption in the integrity of the vessel wall.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Regurgitation of the blood of the heart valves owning to imperfect closing, insufficiency or incompetency of the valves.

Concepts.definition: Regurgitation of the blood of the heart valves owning to imperfect closing, insufficiency or incompetency of the valves.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Normal or abnormal secretions from the vagina. Mucus produced by the cervical glands is discharged from the vagina naturally, especially during the childbearing years. Causes of abnormal vaginal discharge include infectious agents (e.g., Neisseria gonorrhea, Chlamydia trachomatis, Trichomonas, and Candida albicans), the presence of foreign bodies, and cervical or vaginal cancer.

Concepts.definition: Normal or abnormal secretions from the vagina. Mucus produced by the cervical glands is discharged from the vagina naturally, especially during the childbearing years. Causes of abnormal vaginal discharge include infectious agents (e.g., Neisseria gonorrhea, Chlamydia trachomatis, Trichomonas, and Candida albicans), the presence of foreign bodies, and cervical or vaginal cancer.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A smooth, slightly elevated area on the body surface, which is redder or paler than the surrounding skin. It is the typical lesion of urticaria, the dermal evidence of allergy, and in sensitive persons may be provoked by mechanical irritation of the skin.

Concepts.definition: A smooth, slightly elevated area on the body surface, which is redder or paler than the surrounding skin. It is the typical lesion of urticaria, the dermal evidence of allergy, and in sensitive persons may be provoked by mechanical irritation of the skin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any termination of pregnancy happening before the fetus is able to sustain independent life.

Concepts.definition: The unintentional or intentional loss of a pregnancy before 22 weeks gestation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A specific reason explaining why a meaningful value is not available. A meaningful value answers the question posed by a Data Element Concept. In contrast, a Missing Value Reason answers the implicit question "Why is there no 'meaningful' value?", when there is none.

Concepts.definition: A specific reason explaining why a meaningful value is not available. A meaningful value answers the question posed by a Data Element Concept. In contrast, a Missing Value Reason answers the implicit question "Why is there no 'meaningful' value?", when there is none.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A pathological process where the blood starts to coagulate throughout the whole body. This depletes the body of its platelets and coagulation factors, and there is an increased risk of hemorrhage.

Concepts.definition: A pathological process where the blood starts to coagulate throughout the whole body. This depletes the body of its platelets and coagulation factors, and there is an increased risk of hemorrhage.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The shaking movement of the whole body or just a certain part of it, often caused by problems of the neurons responsible for muscle action.

Concepts.definition: The shaking movement of the whole body or just a certain part of it, often caused by problems of the neurons responsible for muscle action.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A bacterial infectious process affecting any part of the urinary tract, most commonly the bladder and the urethra. Symptoms include urinary urgency and frequency, burning sensation during urination, lower abdominal discomfort, and cloudy urine.

Concepts.definition: A bacterial infectious process affecting any part of the urinary tract, most commonly the bladder and the urethra. Symptoms include urinary urgency and frequency, burning sensation during urination, lower abdominal discomfort, and cloudy urine.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A chronic and progressive lung disorder characterized by the loss of elasticity of the bronchial tree and the air sacs, destruction of the air sacs wall, thickening of the bronchial wall, and mucous accumulation in the bronchial tree. The pathologic changes result in the disruption of the air flow in the bronchial airways. Signs and symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, productive cough, and chest tightness. The two main types of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease are chronic obstructive bronchitis and emphysema.

Concepts.definition: A chronic and progressive lung disorder characterized by the loss of elasticity of the bronchial tree and the air sacs, destruction of the air sacs wall, thickening of the bronchial wall, and mucous accumulation in the bronchial tree. The pathologic changes result in the disruption of the air flow in the bronchial airways. Signs and symptoms include shortness of breath, wheezing, productive cough, and chest tightness. The two main types of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease are chronic obstructive bronchitis and emphysema.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blood pressure that is abnormally low.

Concepts.definition: Blood pressure that is abnormally low.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: infections and associated diseases by bacteria, general or unspecified.

Concepts.definition: An acute infectious disorder that is caused by gram positive or gram negative bacteria; representative examples include pneumococcal, streptococcal, salmonella, and meningeal infections.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A benign or malignant neoplasm of the breast parenchyma. It can originate from the ducts, lobules or the breast adipose tissue. Breast neoplasms are much more common in females than males.

Concepts.definition: A benign or malignant neoplasm of the breast parenchyma. It can originate from the ducts, lobules or the breast adipose tissue. Breast neoplasms are much more common in females than males.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A localized collection of blood, usually clotted, in an organ, space, or tissue, due to a break in the wall of a blood vessel.

Concepts.definition: A localized collection of blood, usually clotted, in an organ, space, or tissue, due to a break in the wall of a blood vessel.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Inflammation of the coverings of the brain and/or spinal cord, which consist of the PIA MATER; ARACHNOID; and DURA MATER. Infections (viral, bacterial, and fungal) are the most common causes of this condition, but subarachnoid hemorrhage (HEMORRHAGES, SUBARACHNOID), chemical irritation (chemical MENINGITIS), granulomatous conditions, neoplastic conditions (e.g., carcinomatous meningitis), and other inflammatory conditions may produce this syndrome. (From Joynt, Clinical Neurology, 1994, Ch24, p6)

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by acute inflammation of the meninges of the brain and/or spinal cord.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Flow in the opposite direction from normal, as the casting up of undigested food or gas from the stomach, or the backward flowing of blood into the heart, or between the chambers of the heart when a valve is incompetent.

Concepts.definition: Flow in the opposite direction from normal, as the casting up of undigested food or gas from the stomach, or the backward flowing of blood into the heart, or between the chambers of the heart when a valve is incompetent.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth.

Concepts.definition: Forceful ejection of the contents of the stomach through the mouth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Gross necrosis of the myocardium, as a result of interruption of the blood supply to the area, as in coronary thrombosis.

Concepts.definition: Gross necrosis of the myocardium, as a result of interruption of the blood supply to the area, as in coronary thrombosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is an acute or chronic inflammation in the pelvic cavity.  It is most commonly caused by sexually transmitted diseases, including chlamydia and gonorrhea that have ascended into the uterus, fallopian tubes, or ovaries as a result of intercourse or childbirth, or of surgical procedures, including insertion of IUDs or abortion.  PID may be either symptomatic or asymptomatic.  It may cause infertility and it may raise the risk of ectopic pregnancy.  PID is a disease associated with HIV infection.

Concepts.definition: Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) is an acute or chronic inflammation in the pelvic cavity. It is most commonly caused by sexually transmitted diseases, including chlamydia and gonorrhea that have ascended into the uterus, fallopian tubes, or ovaries as a result of intercourse or childbirth, or of surgical procedures, including insertion of IUDs or abortion. PID may be either symptomatic or asymptomatic. It may cause infertility and it may raise the risk of ectopic pregnancy. PID is a disease associated with HIV infection.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A mental state characterized by a lack of clear and orderly thought and behavior.

Concepts.definition: A mental state characterized by a lack of clear and orderly thought and behavior.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disease of the heart muscle or myocardium proper. Cardiomyopathies may be classified as either primary or secondary, on the basis of etiology, or on the pathophysiology of the lesion: hypertrophic, dilated, or restrictive.

Concepts.definition: A disease of the heart muscle or myocardium proper. Cardiomyopathies may be classified as either primary or secondary, on the basis of etiology, or on the pathophysiology of the lesion: hypertrophic, dilated, or restrictive.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A peripheral (mature) T-cell lymphoma, consisting of usually large anaplastic, CD30 positive cells.  Majority of cases are positive for the anaplastic large cell lymphoma (ALK) protein.  The most frequently seen genetic alteration is a t(2;5) translocation.  Majority of patients present with advanced disease.  The most important prognostic indicator is ALK positivity, which has been associated with a favorable prognosis. (WHO, 2001)

Concepts.definition: A peripheral (mature) T-cell lymphoma, consisting of usually large anaplastic, CD30 positive cells. The majority of cases are positive for the anaplastic large cell lymphoma (ALK) protein. The most frequently seen genetic alteration is a t(2;5) translocation. Majority of patients present with advanced disease. The most important prognostic indicator is ALK positivity, which has been associated with a favorable prognosis. (WHO, 2001)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Fever, also known as pyrexia, is the elevation of the body's temperature above the upper limit of normal, usually taken as 37.7 degrees C.  Most fevers are caused by infections and almost all infectious diseases cause fever. (Wikipedia)

Concepts.definition: Elevation of body temperature above normal due to inflammatory or immune responses.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by a decrease in the level of oxygen in the body.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by a decrease in the level of oxygen in the body.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Sudden cessation of the pumping function of the heart, with disappearance of arterial blood pressure, connoting either ventricular fibrillation or ventricular standstill.

Concepts.definition: The sudden cessation of cardiac activity in an individual who becomes unresponsive, without normal breathing and no signs of circulation. Cardiac arrest may be reversed by CPR, and/or defibrillation, cardioversion or cardiac pacing.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Inability of the heart to pump blood at an adequate rate to meet tissue metabolic requirements or the ability to do so only at an elevated filling pressure.

Concepts.definition: Inability of the heart to pump blood at an adequate rate to meet tissue metabolic requirements. Clinical symptoms of heart failure include: unusual dyspnea on light exertion, recurrent dyspnea occurring in the supine position, fluid retention or rales, jugular venous distension, pulmonary edema on physical exam, or pulmonary edema on chest x-ray presumed to be cardiac dysfunction.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A condition of the newborn marked by dyspnea with cyanosis, most frequently occurring in premature infants, children of diabetic mothers and infants delivered by cesarean section, and sometimes with no predisposing cause.

Concepts.definition: A condition beginning in the first day of life that results from inadequate surfactant production, causing increased work of breathing and impaired gas exchange.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An issue is based on the patient.

Concepts.definition: An issue is based on the patient.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The outcome of a laboratory test.

Concepts.definition: The outcome of a laboratory test.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A carcinoma arising from the breast, most commonly the terminal ductal-lobular unit. It is the most common malignant tumor in females. Risk factors include country of birth, family history, menstrual and reproductive history, fibrocystic disease and epithelial hyperplasia, exogenous estrogens, contraceptive agents, and ionizing radiation. The vast majority of breast carcinomas are adenocarcinomas (ductal or lobular). Breast carcinoma spreads by direct invasion, by the lymphatic route, and by the blood vessel route. The most common site of lymph node involvement is the axilla.

Concepts.definition: A carcinoma arising from the breast, most commonly the terminal ductal-lobular unit. It is the most common malignant tumor in females. Risk factors include country of birth, family history, menstrual and reproductive history, fibrocystic disease and epithelial hyperplasia, exogenous estrogens, contraceptive agents, and ionizing radiation. The vast majority of breast carcinomas are adenocarcinomas (ductal or lobular). Breast carcinoma spreads by direct invasion, by the lymphatic route, and by the blood vessel route. The most common site of lymph node involvement is the axilla.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A level of awareness that can be described as consistently not responsive to stimuli.

Concepts.definition: An inability to purposefully respond to stimuli.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by a sudden, involuntary skeletal muscular contractions of cerebral or brain stem origin.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by a sudden, involuntary skeletal muscular contractions of cerebral or brain stem origin.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by melancholic feelings of grief or unhappiness.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by melancholic feelings of grief or unhappiness.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Fluid collection within the pericardial sac, usually due to inflammation.

Concepts.definition: Fluid collection within the pericardial sac, usually due to inflammation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a cardiac rhythm originating in the ventricles. The heart rate is usually regular and ranging between 30-40 beats per minute (the intrinsic ventricular rate), but can be higher or lower.

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin with a rate less than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The occurrence of a premature ventricular complex near the peak of the T wave in electrocardiography; it may lead to ventricular tachycardia or fibrillation.

Concepts.longName: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the R wave of a premature ventricular complex occurs on top of the T wave of the preceding beat. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment depression below the baseline, often described as up sloping, down sloping or horizontal.

Concepts.longName: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment depression below the baseline, often described as up sloping, down sloping or horizontal.

PermissibleValues.value: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atypical rapid polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a characteristic rotation of the QRS complex around the isoelectric baseline, occurring in the setting of a prolonged QT interval. In addition, the QRS complex displays a periodic waxing and waning of amplitude on the electrogram.

Concepts.longName: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atypical rapid polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a characteristic rotation of the QRS complex around the isoelectric baseline, occurring in the setting of a prolonged QT interval. In addition, the QRS complex displays a periodic waxing and waning of amplitude on the electrocardiogram.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A common bacterial species found especially on nasal mucous membrane and skin (hair follicles); bacterial species that produces exotoxins including those that cause toxic shock syndrome, with resulting skin rash, and renal, hepatic, and central nervous system disease, and an enterotoxin associated with food poisoning; it causes furunculosis, cellulitis, pyemia, pneumonia, osteomyelitis, endocarditis, suppuration of wounds, other infections; also a cause of infection in burn patients; humans are the chief reservoir.

Concepts.definition: A common bacterial species found especially on nasal mucous membrane and skin (hair follicles); bacterial species that produces exotoxins including those that cause toxic shock syndrome, with resulting skin rash, and renal, hepatic, and central nervous system disease, and an enterotoxin associated with food poisoning; it causes furunculosis, cellulitis, pyemia, pneumonia, osteomyelitis, endocarditis, suppuration of wounds, other infections; also a cause of infection in burn patients; humans are the chief reservoir.

PermissibleValues.value: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Evaluation of the interval from the end of ventricular depolarization to the onset of the T wave; it is usually isoelectric in normal subjects.

Concepts.longName: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment elevation above the baseline.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The condition of having a developing embryo or fetus in the body, after union of an ovum and spermatozoon. (Dorland, 27th ed)

Concepts.definition: The state or condition of having a developing embryo or fetus in the body (uterus), after union of an ovum and spermatozoon, during the period from conception to birth.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormally high blood pressure.

Concepts.definition: Blood pressure that is abnormally high.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sudden, nonconvulsive loss of neurologic function due to an ischemic or hemorrhagic intracranial vascular event. In general, cerebrovascular accidents are classified by anatomic location in the brain, vascular distribution, etiology, age of the affected individual, and hemorrhagic vs. nonhemorrhagic nature. (From Adams et al., Principles of Neurology, 6th ed, pp777-810)

Concepts.definition: A sudden loss of neurological function secondary to hemorrhage or ischemia in the brain parenchyma due to a vascular event.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of a rapid grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude. The rate is typically greater than 300 bpm. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of a rapid grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude. The rate is typically greater than 300 bpm. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Altered reactivity to an antigen, which can result in pathologic reactions upon subsequent exposure to that particular antigen.

Concepts.definition: An immune response that occurs following exposure to an innocuous antigen, but that does not require the presence of preformed antibodies to the antigen.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which impaired conduction or automaticity within the sinus node results in the failure of impulse transmission from the sinoatrial node. This is manifested as dropped P waves during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which impaired conduction or automaticity within the sinus node results in the failure of impulse transmission from the sinoatrial node. This is manifested as dropped P waves during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A device problem is not adequately described by any other term. Note: this code must not be used unless there is no other feasible code.

Concepts.longName: Appropriate Term/Code Not Available Problem Code
Concepts.definition: A device problem is not adequately described by any other term. Note: this code must not be used unless there is no other feasible code.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A heart condition marked by paroxysms of chest pain due to reduced oxygen to the heart.

Concepts.definition: Paroxysms of chest pain due to reduced oxygen to the heart.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An acute inflammatory reaction resulting from the release of histamine and histamine-like substances from mast cells, causing a hypersensitivity immune response.  Clinically, it presents with breathing difficulty, dizziness, hypotension, cyanosis and loss of consciousness, and may lead to death.

Concepts.definition: Progression of anaphylaxis into systemic shock, which is characterized by significant reduction in tissue perfusion which leads to hypoxia and hypotension, and can lead to death if untreated.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an organized rhythmic contraction of the atria which is generally at a rate of 200-300 beats per minute.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of an organized, regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of 240-340 beats per minute. Multiple P waves typically appear in the inferior leads in a saw tooth-like pattern between the QRS complexes. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggregation of blood factors, primarily platelets and fibrin with entrapment of cellular elements, frequently causing vascular obstruction at the point of its formation.

Concepts.definition: An aggregation of blood factors, primarily platelets and fibrin with entrapment of cellular elements, frequently causing vascular obstruction at the point of its formation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Blurred vision is the loss of visual acuity (sharpness of vision) resulting in a loss of ability to see small details. (from MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia)

Concepts.definition: Blurred vision is the loss of visual acuity (sharpness of vision) resulting in a loss of ability to see small details. (from MedlinePlus Medical Encyclopedia)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A mass in the mammary gland, either mobile or immobile. Once the mass has reached the size of a small garden pea, it can be detected by palpation. With mammography a larger number of early breast cancers are being detected since this techniques allows detection prior to the point at which the mass can be felt. Breast masses are not always malignant. Benign fibrocystic breast disease is not uncommon. A fine needle biopsy aspiration can distinguish a cystic mass from a solid one.

Concepts.definition: A mass in the mammary gland, either mobile or immobile. Once the mass has reached the size of a small garden pea, it can be detected by palpation. With mammography a larger number of early breast cancers are being detected since this techniques allows detection prior to the point at which the mass can be felt. Breast masses are not always malignant. Benign fibrocystic breast disease is not uncommon. A fine needle biopsy aspiration can distinguish a cystic mass from a solid one.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An acute or chronic inflammatory process affecting the bronchi.

Concepts.definition: An acute or chronic inflammatory process affecting the bronchi.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The loss of cerebrospinal fluid into the surrounding tissues.

Concepts.definition: The loss of cerebrospinal fluid into the surrounding tissues.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Chills; a sensation of cold that often marks the start of an infection and the development of a fever.

Concepts.definition: Shivering or moderate tremors of the body often accompanied by a cold sensation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A state of profound unconsciousness associated with markedly depressed cerebral activity. Causes include central nervous system damage, intoxication, and metabolic abnormalities.

Concepts.definition: A state of profound unconsciousness associated with markedly depressed cerebral activity. Causes include central nervous system damage, intoxication, and metabolic abnormalities.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Ocular pain which may be very intense, accompanied by corneal epithelium damage, conjunctival injection, lacrimation, blepharospasm, photophobia and hazy vision following corneal edema caused by overwear of contact lenses, principally the PMMA type.

Concepts.definition: Ocular pain which may be very intense, accompanied by corneal epithelium damage, conjunctival injection, lacrimation, blepharospasm, photophobia and hazy vision following corneal edema caused by overwear of contact lenses, principally the PMMA type.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Area of epithelial tissue loss from corneal surface; associated with inflammatory cells in the cornea and anterior chamber.

Concepts.definition: Area of epithelial tissue loss from corneal surface; associated with inflammatory cells in the cornea and anterior chamber.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Difficulty swallowing.

Concepts.definition: A symptom referring to difficulty in swallowing. It may be observed in patients with stroke, motor neuron disorders, cancer of the throat or mouth, head and neck injuries, Parkinson disease, and multiple sclerosis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A process caused by injury or disease or aging and characterized by a partial/complete disruption of tissue. The disruption may be temporary or permanent and may be associated with either (1) impairment or (2) loss of function of the affected organ(s) or system(s).

Concepts.definition: A process caused by injury or disease or aging and characterized by a partial/complete disruption of tissue. The disruption may be temporary or permanent and may be associated with either (1) impairment or (2) loss of function of the affected organ(s) or system(s).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A rupture in the uterus due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

Concepts.definition: A rupture in the uterus due to traumatic or pathologic processes.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tachycardia arising distal to bundle of His, with a rate greater than 100 beats per minute.

Concepts.definition: A disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Abnormal permanent enlargement of the lung air spaces distal to terminal bronchiole not resulted from wall destruction, e.g. due to loss of opposite lung.

Concepts.definition: Abnormal permanent enlargement of the lung air spaces distal to terminal bronchiole not resulted from wall destruction, e.g. due to loss of opposite lung.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A disorder acquired through sexual contact.

Concepts.definition: A disorder acquired through sexual contact.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A severe illness caused by infection with staphylococcus aureus and characterized by high fever of sudden onset, vomiting, diarrhea, and myalgia, followed by hypotension and in severe cases, shock; a sunburn-like rash with peeling of the skin, especially of the palms and soles, occurs during the acute phase.

Concepts.definition: A rare acute life-threatening systemic bacterial noncontagious illness caused by any of several related staphylococcal exotoxins. It is characterized by high fever, hypotension, rash, multi-organ dysfunction, and cutaneous desquamation during the early convalescent period. The toxins affect the host immune system, causing an exuberant and pathological host inflammatory response. Laboratory findings include leukocytosis, elevated prothrombin time, hypoalbuminemia, hypocalcemia, and pyuria.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Death in utero; failure of the product of conception to show evidence of respiration, heart beat, or definite movement of a voluntary muscle after expulsion from the uterus, with no possibility of resuscitation.

Concepts.definition: Death of a fetus after 10 weeks gestation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery. Cases of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome are not included in this definition.

Concepts.definition: Progressive and life-threatening pulmonary distress in the absence of an underlying pulmonary condition, usually following major trauma or surgery. Cases of neonatal respiratory distress syndrome are not included in this definition.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Injuries to tissues caused by contact with heat, steam, chemicals (BURNS, CHEMICAL), electricity (BURNS, ELECTRIC), or the like.

Concepts.definition: A traumatic injury involving interruption of tissue cohesiveness that results from exposure to caustic chemicals, extreme heat, extreme cold or excessive radiation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Partial or complete opacity of the crystalline lens of one or both eyes that decreases visual acuity and eventually results in blindness.  Some cataracts appear in infancy or in childhood, but most develop in older individuals. (Diagnostic Surgical Pathology, 3rd ed.) --2003

Concepts.definition: Partial or complete opacity of the crystalline lens of one or both eyes that decreases visual acuity and eventually results in blindness. Some cataracts appear in infancy or in childhood, but most develop in older individuals. (Sternberg Diagnostic Surgical Pathology, 3rd ed.)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Partial or complete paralysis of the facial muscles of one side of a person's face. It is caused by damage to the seventh cranial nerve. It is usually temporary but it may recur.

Concepts.definition: Partial or complete paralysis of the facial muscles of one side of a person's face. It is caused by damage to the seventh cranial nerve. It is usually temporary but it may recur.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A sudden, temporary onset of body warmth, flushing, and sweating (often associated with menopause).

Concepts.definition: A temporary feeling of intense body warmth, flushing, sometimes accompanied by sweating. A common, symptom of menopause; other conditions that can produce hot flushes include antidepressants and drugs blocking the effect of estrogens, carcinoid tumors and a sensitivity to sulfites or other food additives.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The presence of a hole or other type of opening in the esophageal wall through which the contents of the esophagus can pass into the mediastinum. The most common cause of esophageal perforation is injury during a medical procedure such as esophagoscopy or placement of a naso-gastric tube; and pathologic process such as neoplasm or gastric reflux with ulceration. Less common causes include injuries from penetrating or blunt trauma or injury to the esophagus during an operation on another organ, mechanical problem such as violent retching or vomiting; ingestion of a foreign body or caustic agents. The condition often results in infection of the mediastinum and mediastinitis.

Concepts.definition: The presence of a hole or other type of opening in the esophageal wall through which the contents of the esophagus can pass into the mediastinum. The most common cause of esophageal perforation is injury during a medical procedure such as esophagoscopy or placement of a naso-gastric tube; and pathologic process such as neoplasm or gastric reflux with ulceration. Less common causes include injuries from penetrating or blunt trauma or injury to the esophagus during an operation on another organ, mechanical problem such as violent retching or vomiting; ingestion of a foreign body or caustic agents. The condition often results in infection of the mediastinum and mediastinitis.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues causing disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure. It is caused by direct injury to the lung parenchyma or congestive heart failure. The symptoms may appear suddenly or gradually. Suddenly appearing symptoms include difficulty breathing, feeling of suffocation, and coughing associated with frothy sputum. Gradually appearing symptoms include difficulty breathing while lying in bed, shortness of breath during activity, and weight gain (in patients with congestive heart failure).

Concepts.definition: Accumulation of fluid in the lung tissues causing disturbance of the gas exchange that may lead to respiratory failure. It is caused by direct injury to the lung parenchyma or congestive heart failure. The symptoms may appear suddenly or gradually. ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An intense itching sensation.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Spots before the eyes caused by opaque cell fragments in the vitreous humor or lens.:A disorder characterized by an individual seeing spots before their eyes. Concepts.definition: Spots before the eyes caused by opaque cell fragments in the vitreous humor or lens.

Concepts.definition: The presence of an acquired hole in the heart. Cardiac perforation may or may not be symptomatic and may or may not be self sealing. (ACC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An unusual or extreme paleness, state of decreased skin or mucosal coloration.

Concepts.definition: An unusual or extreme paleness, state of decreased skin or mucosal coloration.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Toxicity; the degree to which something is poisonous.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The formation or development of an ulcer.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: widely occurring intracellular herpesvirus characterized by narrow host specificity and slow reproduction (latency); causes a variety of pathologies in mammals, including AIDS related oculopathy in humans.

Concepts.definition: A genus of the family herpesviridae, subfamily betaherpesvirinae, infecting the salivary glands, liver, spleen, lungs, eyes, and other organs, in which they produce characteristically enlarged cells with intranuclear inclusions.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A malignant (clonal) proliferation of B- or T- lymphocytes which involves the lymph nodes, bone marrow and/or extranodal sites.  This category includes Non-Hodgkin's lymphomas and Hodgkin's lymphomas. -- 2003

Concepts.definition: A malignant (clonal) proliferation of B- lymphocytes or T- lymphocytes which involves the lymph nodes, bone marrow and/or extranodal sites. This category includes Non-Hodgkin lymphomas and Hodgkin lymphomas.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Information regarding the subject is unknown or inaccessible at this time.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Any abnormality, anatomical or biochemical, evident at birth or during the neonatal period.

Concepts.definition: Any abnormality, anatomical or biochemical, evident at birth or during the neonatal period.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A tumor composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues.  Malignant neoplasms usually metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision.  The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas (adenocarcinomas or squamous cell carcinomas), Hodgkin's and non-Hodgkin's lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas. -- 2004

Concepts.definition: A neoplasm composed of atypical neoplastic, often pleomorphic cells that invade other tissues. Malignant neoplasms often metastasize to distant anatomic sites and may recur after excision. The most common malignant neoplasms are carcinomas, Hodgkin and non-Hodgkin lymphomas, leukemias, melanomas, and sarcomas.
